'Triplet oxygen' (or ' 3O 2') is the ground state of the
oxygen molecule. The electron configuration of the molecule has two unpaired
electrons occupying two degenerate molecular orbitals. These orbitals are
classified as antibonding, so the O-O bond is weaker than the N-N bond in
molecular nitrogen, where all bonding molecular orbitals are filled.
